Note:
FreeBSD ARM64 System Call Interface

This file implements FreeBSD ARM64 (AArch64) system calls.

Platform-specific details:
- Platform: FreeBSD ARM64
- Syscall mechanism: SVC instruction (svc #0)
- Syscall number register: X8
- Argument registers: X0-X5 (up to 6 arguments)
- Return value: X0 (positive on success, negative errno on error)

FreeBSD syscall convention (ARM64):
- X8 = syscall number
- X0-X5 = arguments 1-6
- Stack = arguments 7+ (if needed)
- X0 = return value (or -errno on error)
- Carry flag in CPSR indicates error (but typically check for negative return)

FreeBSD syscall numbers differ from Linux and Darwin.
This file provides both syscall number constants and wrapper functions.

Dependencies: None (uses inline assembly for syscalls)
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory

Note:
============================================================================
SYSCALL NUMBER CONSTANTS
============================================================================
:End Note

Note:
FreeBSD syscall numbers (from sys/kern/syscalls.master)
These are specific to FreeBSD and differ from Linux/Darwin
:End Note

Process called "freebsd_arm64_SYS_SYSCALL" returns Integer:
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "freebsd_arm64_SYS_EXIT" returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
FreeBSD does not provide a distinct exit_group(2) system call. The kernel
treats `_exit(2)` (BSD syscall #1) as a whole-process termination primitive:
sys_exit() in `sys/kern/kern_exit.c` calls exit1(p, ...) which tears down
every thread in the proc by sending each kernel thread an exit signal and
reaping them in turn. Linux distinguishes between `exit` (single-thread,
syscall 60/93) and `exit_group` (all threads, syscall 231/94), but on
FreeBSD the single `exit` syscall fulfils both semantics. We therefore
alias SYS_EXIT_GROUP to SYS_EXIT=1 so cross-platform callers obtain the
correct "terminate all threads" behaviour without conditional code.
Source: FreeBSD `sys/kern/kern_exit.c` exit1(); `sys/sys/syscall.h`
SYS_exit=1 (no separate SYS_exit_group entry).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Nullary Process accessor returning the constant integer 1. The dispatcher
routes `SYS_EXIT_GROUP from Syscall` to this proc on freebsd_arm64 targets
via the bare-name pattern still in force during Wave 1. The numeric value
is identical to SYS_EXIT because FreeBSD's exit(2) already exhibits
exit_group semantics; no fallback or wrapper logic is required.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant return; compiler-inlined at every call site. Zero runtime cost.
Callers should prefer SYS_EXIT directly on FreeBSD; SYS_EXIT_GROUP exists
only to honour the 66-proc cross-platform dispatcher contract.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a syscall number has no direct security state. Callers that
invoke `syscall_1(SYS_EXIT_GROUP(), status)` cause whole-process
termination including any privileged threads, child threads holding
mutexes, and threads in uninterruptible kernel waits. Use in a sandbox
or seccomp-filtered process only after auditing the teardown order of
shared resources (file descriptors, mmapped regions, IPC handles).
@End Security_Scope

Process called "freebsd_arm64_SYS_EXIT_GROUP" returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

