Process called "freebsd_arm64_SYS_BREAK" returns Integer:
    Return 17
End Process

@Reasoning
FreeBSD's historical `break(2)` system call (BSD syscall #17) is the heap
data-segment break primitive inherited from 4.4BSD. The POSIX/Linux name
for this interface is `brk(2)`. On FreeBSD `break` and `brk` refer to the
same kernel entry; the BSD-name accessor SYS_BREAK above and the Linux/
cross-platform-name accessor SYS_BRK below resolve to the identical
numeric value 17. Cross-platform code written against the dispatcher's
bare-name API expects to find SYS_BRK on every platform; FreeBSD exposes
it natively (unlike Darwin, which removed brk and routes heap growth
through Mach `vm_allocate`).
Source: FreeBSD `sys/sys/syscall.h` SYS_break=17;
`sys/kern/sys_process.c` sys_break() handler; FreeBSD 14 syscalls.master
"break BSD-only".
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Nullary Process accessor returning the constant integer 17. Aliased to
SYS_BREAK at the source level (both procs return 17) so callers may use
either the BSD-historical name or the Linux/POSIX-portable name without
behavioural divergence. The dispatcher routes `SYS_BRK from Syscall` to
this proc on freebsd_arm64 targets via the bare-name pattern still in
force during Wave 1.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant return; compiler-inlined at every call site. Zero runtime cost.
Heap growth on FreeBSD is conventionally performed via `mmap(MAP_ANON)`
rather than `brk`/`sbrk` in modern allocators; callers in performance-
critical paths should prefer SYS_MMAP for new anonymous regions and use
SYS_BRK only for legacy data-segment compatibility.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a syscall number has no direct security state. Callers issuing
`syscall_1(SYS_BRK(), addr)` request data-segment growth without bounds
checking by the wrapper; the kernel enforces RLIMIT_DATA via
`setrlimit(RLIMIT_DATA, ...)`. Untrusted code in a sandbox should set a
restrictive RLIMIT_DATA before granting access to this syscall, or filter
SYS_BRK through Capsicum capability mode (sys/cap_*).
@End Security_Scope

