Process called "freebsd_arm64_SYS_CPUSET_GETAFFINITY" returns Integer:
    Return 487
End Process

@Reasoning
FreeBSD does not expose a syscall literally named `sched_getaffinity`.
The POSIX `sched_getaffinity(3)` interface is implemented in libc on
top of the kernel-level `cpuset_getaffinity(2)` system call (FreeBSD
syscall #487). The two interfaces are semantically equivalent for the
purpose of querying which CPUs a thread or process is bound to. Linux
maps `sched_getaffinity` to a distinct syscall number (204 on x86_64,
123 on arm64). To preserve the 66-proc cross-platform dispatcher API
on FreeBSD ARM64 we alias SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY to 487 so that callers
using the portable name receive the kernel-native interface that
implements the same semantics. Note that `cpuset_getaffinity(2)` takes
a richer argument signature than Linux's `sched_getaffinity(2)`
(level, which, id, setsize, mask) versus (pid, setsize, mask); high-
level wrappers must translate the argument shape, not just the
syscall number.
Source: FreeBSD `sys/sys/syscall.h` SYS_cpuset_getaffinity=487;
FreeBSD `sys/kern/kern_cpuset.c` sys_cpuset_getaffinity();
FreeBSD 14 `cpuset_getaffinity(2)` man page; POSIX.1-2017
sched_getaffinity rationale.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Nullary Process accessor returning the constant integer 487, identical
to SYS_CPUSET_GETAFFINITY above. The dispatcher routes
`SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY from Syscall` to this proc on freebsd_arm64
targets via the bare-name pattern still in force during Wave 1.
Cross-platform callers that issue this syscall must arrange the
FreeBSD-specific argument layout (CPU_LEVEL_WHICH=3,
CPU_WHICH_TID/PID/CPUSET, target id, set size, mask pointer) at the
call site; the wrapper does not translate Linux-style
`(pid, setsize, mask)` into the FreeBSD-style 5-argument form.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant return; compiler-inlined at every call site. Zero runtime
cost. Affinity queries are infrequent (typically once at thread
startup or in scheduler-monitoring code paths), so even the underlying
syscall cost is rarely on a hot path. Repeated queries on the same
thread are stable across the thread's lifetime unless a cpuset(2)
reassignment occurs, so caching the result at the caller level is
safe for the common case.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a syscall number has no direct security state. The
underlying `cpuset_getaffinity(2)` enforces credential checks per
FreeBSD's kern_cpuset.c: a caller must have appropriate privileges
(typically own the target proc/thread or have PRIV_SCHED_CPUSET) to
query another principal's affinity. Capsicum capability mode further
restricts which cpuset levels/whiches are accessible. Callers must
not assume affinity information about other processes is freely
queryable.
@End Security_Scope

