Note:
============================================================================
GENERIC SYSCALL WRAPPERS
============================================================================
:End Note

Note:
FreeBSD ARM64 syscall convention:
- X8 = syscall number
- X0-X5 = arguments 1-6
- Stack = arguments 7+
- Return value in X0
:End Note

Process called "freebsd_arm64_syscall_0" takes syscall_number as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: FreeBSD ARM64 syscall with 0 arguments
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into X8
        ldr x8, [fp, #-8]

        # Execute syscall
        svc #0

        # Store result from X0
        str x0, [fp, #-16]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "freebsd_arm64_syscall_1" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: FreeBSD ARM64 syscall with 1 argument
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into X8
        ldr x8, [fp, #-8]

        # Load argument 1 into X0
        ldr x0, [fp, #-16]

        # Execute syscall
        svc #0

        # Store result from X0
        str x0, [fp, #-24]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "freebsd_arm64_syscall_2" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: FreeBSD ARM64 syscall with 2 arguments
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into X8
        ldr x8, [fp, #-8]

        # Load arguments 1-2 into X0-X1
        ldr x0, [fp, #-16]
        ldr x1, [fp, #-24]

        # Execute syscall
        svc #0

        # Store result from X0
        str x0, [fp, #-32]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "freebsd_arm64_syscall_3" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: FreeBSD ARM64 syscall with 3 arguments
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into X8
        ldr x8, [fp, #-8]

        # Load arguments 1-3 into X0-X2
        ldr x0, [fp, #-16]
        ldr x1, [fp, #-24]
        ldr x2, [fp, #-32]

        # Execute syscall
        svc #0

        # Store result from X0
        str x0, [fp, #-40]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "freebsd_arm64_syscall_4" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer, arg4 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: FreeBSD ARM64 syscall with 4 arguments
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into X8
        ldr x8, [fp, #-8]

        # Load arguments 1-4 into X0-X3
        ldr x0, [fp, #-16]
        ldr x1, [fp, #-24]
        ldr x2, [fp, #-32]
        ldr x3, [fp, #-40]

        # Execute syscall
        svc #0

        # Store result from X0
        str x0, [fp, #-48]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "freebsd_arm64_syscall_5" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer, arg4 as Integer, arg5 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: FreeBSD ARM64 syscall with 5 arguments
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into X8
        ldr x8, [fp, #-8]

        # Load arguments 1-5 into X0-X4
        ldr x0, [fp, #-16]
        ldr x1, [fp, #-24]
        ldr x2, [fp, #-32]
        ldr x3, [fp, #-40]
        ldr x4, [fp, #-48]

        # Execute syscall
        svc #0

        # Store result from X0
        str x0, [fp, #-56]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "freebsd_arm64_syscall_6" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer, arg4 as Integer, arg5 as Integer, arg6 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: FreeBSD ARM64 syscall with 6 arguments
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into X8
        ldr x8, [fp, #-8]

        # Load arguments 1-6 into X0-X5
        ldr x0, [fp, #-16]
        ldr x1, [fp, #-24]
        ldr x2, [fp, #-32]
        ldr x3, [fp, #-40]
        ldr x4, [fp, #-48]
        ldr x5, [fp, #-56]

        # Execute syscall
        svc #0

        # Store result from X0
        str x0, [fp, #-64]
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
DISPATCHER-NAMED SYSCALL WRAPPERS (syscall_<name> bare form)
============================================================================
:End Note

@Reasoning
The cross-platform syscall dispatcher exposes 10 `syscall_<name>` bare-name
procs (syscall_read, syscall_write, syscall_open, syscall_close,
syscall_exit, syscall_brk, syscall_mmap, syscall_munmap, syscall_fstat,
syscall_lseek). Each platform module must export the same names so the
dispatcher's bare-name routing can resolve to platform-correct ABI
behaviour. On FreeBSD ARM64 every wrapper routes through the correct
`syscall_N` generic dispatcher with the matching SYS_* number from this
file.

These are NOT duplicates of the lower-section `read`/`write`/`open`/...
wrappers: those use POSIX-style short names for compatibility with the
v0.0.7.5-era Runa standard library; the `syscall_<name>` forms are what
the platform-dispatch infrastructure expects per the P2-B design's
"Per-platform syscall inventory" section.

Source for syscall numbers: FreeBSD `sys/sys/syscall.h` (the syscall
table is shared between freebsd_x64 and freebsd_arm64; only the ABI
mechanism differs: arm64 uses `svc #0` with X8=syscall_num and X0..X5
as argument registers, x64 uses `syscall` with RAX=syscall_num and
RDI/RSI/RDX/R10/R8/R9 as argument registers). FreeBSD 14 syscalls.master
confirms: read=3, write=4, open=5, close=6, exit=1, break/brk=17,
mmap=477 (with the 64-bit-clean signature), munmap=73, fstat=189,
lseek=478.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each wrapper computes the syscall number via the matching SYS_*
accessor (itself a constant return on freebsd_arm64) and forwards
arguments to the `syscall_N` generic dispatcher matching the arity.
The generic dispatcher loads X8 with the syscall number and X0-X5 with
arguments, then issues `svc #0` and returns X0. Negative X0 values are
FreeBSD-ABI errno indications which the wrapper propagates unchanged
to the caller (FreeBSD's calling convention also sets the carry flag
in PSTATE on syscall error; this wrapper does not inspect carry, so
callers that need to distinguish errno from large valid returns
should compare against the `-errno` range explicitly).

Argument-passing convention:
- syscall_read(fd, buf, count) -> SYS_READ(3) via syscall_3
- syscall_write(fd, buf, count) -> SYS_WRITE(4) via syscall_3
- syscall_open(path, flags, mode) -> SYS_OPEN(5) via syscall_3
- syscall_close(fd) -> SYS_CLOSE(6) via syscall_1
- syscall_exit(status) -> SYS_EXIT(1) via syscall_1
- syscall_brk(addr) -> SYS_BRK(17) via syscall_1
- syscall_mmap(addr, len, prot, flags, fd, offset) -> SYS_MMAP(477) via syscall_6
- syscall_munmap(addr, len) -> SYS_MUNMAP(73) via syscall_2
- syscall_fstat(fd, statbuf) -> SYS_FSTAT(189) via syscall_2
- syscall_lseek(fd, offset, whence) -> SYS_LSEEK(478) via syscall_3

Note on mmap: FreeBSD's modern `mmap(2)` is syscall 477 (the 64-bit
offset-clean entry), not the legacy 71 (also present in this file for
historical completeness). The `syscall_mmap` wrapper routes through
the 477 entry so the 6th argument is a full 64-bit byte offset, which
matches the cross-platform dispatcher contract. The legacy 71 entry
is retained as SYS_MMAP only for source-level compatibility with old
BSD code; callers wanting the 64-bit offset interface should use
`syscall_mmap` or `SYS_MMAP` referencing 477 (which is what this file
returns as SYS_MMAP near the end of the SYS_* table).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Each wrapper compiles down to: load constant syscall number, marshal
arguments through the stack frame to X0-X5/X8, issue `svc #0`. Total
cost is dominated by the kernel-mode trap, not the wrapper's Runa-
level indirection. The wrapper itself adds 2-3 instructions of glue
beyond the generic syscall_N body. Do not introduce caching or
memoisation; syscalls are not pure functions and the kernel cost
dominates.

For hot-path syscall sites (e.g. read/write in tight I/O loops), prefer
calling the generic `syscall_3` directly with the SYS_* constant
inlined, avoiding the intermediate wrapper. The wrapper exists for
dispatcher contract compliance, not as a recommended fast-path entry.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
File-descriptor and pointer arguments are passed verbatim to the
kernel. The wrapper performs no validation; the kernel enforces all
access controls (UID/GID, jail(8) confinement, Capsicum capability
rights on the file descriptors, MAC framework policy, sysctl
hardening). Callers must NOT use these wrappers to issue syscalls on
behalf of an untrusted source without Capsicum sandboxing at the
process level.

In particular:
- syscall_open: untrusted `path` strings can traverse the filesystem
  subject only to DAC, jail(2) chroot, and Capsicum policy; sandboxed
  callers must enter capability mode via `cap_enter(2)` before
  invoking, after which absolute paths and `..` traversal become
  unavailable.
- syscall_mmap with PROT_EXEC: writable+executable mappings are a
  W^X violation; callers should request PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE then
  mprotect-up to PROT_EXEC after content is written. FreeBSD's
  `kern.elf64.allow_wx` sysctl can be set to 0 to enforce W^X
  system-wide.
- syscall_exit: on FreeBSD `_exit(2)` terminates the entire process
  (all threads), unlike Linux where SYS_EXIT only terminates the
  calling thread. To exit a single thread on FreeBSD use SYS_THR_EXIT
  (431) via syscall_1 directly.

Errno propagation: kernel returns -errno in X0 for failure. The
wrapper returns this verbatim; positive values are syscall results
(e.g. byte counts, file descriptors, addresses). Caller MUST check
sign of return value before treating it as a syscall result. FreeBSD
also sets the PSTATE carry flag on error in addition to negative-X0
encoding; this wrapper does not inspect carry, so callers reliant
on the carry signal must use a lower-level inline-asm entry.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "freebsd_arm64_syscall_read" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Read from file descriptor; routes through SYS_READ (3) on freebsd_arm64
    Let syscall_num be freebsd_arm64_SYS_READ()
    Return freebsd_arm64_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, buffer, count)
End Process

Process called "freebsd_arm64_syscall_write" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Write to file descriptor; routes through SYS_WRITE (4) on freebsd_arm64
    Let syscall_num be freebsd_arm64_SYS_WRITE()
    Return freebsd_arm64_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, buffer, count)
End Process

Process called "freebsd_arm64_syscall_open" takes filename as Integer, flags as Integer, mode as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Open file; routes through SYS_OPEN (5) on freebsd_arm64
    Let syscall_num be freebsd_arm64_SYS_OPEN()
    Return freebsd_arm64_syscall_3(syscall_num, filename, flags, mode)
End Process

Process called "freebsd_arm64_syscall_close" takes fd as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Close file descriptor; routes through SYS_CLOSE (6) on freebsd_arm64
    Let syscall_num be freebsd_arm64_SYS_CLOSE()
    Return freebsd_arm64_syscall_1(syscall_num, fd)
End Process

Process called "freebsd_arm64_syscall_exit" takes status as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Terminate calling process; routes through SYS_EXIT (1) on freebsd_arm64
    FreeBSD _exit(2) terminates the WHOLE process (all threads), unlike
    Linux where SYS_EXIT only terminates the calling thread. The Return
    statement is unreachable on success but required to satisfy the
    dispatcher's Integer-return contract.
    :End Note
    Let syscall_num be freebsd_arm64_SYS_EXIT()
    Return freebsd_arm64_syscall_1(syscall_num, status)
End Process

Process called "freebsd_arm64_syscall_brk" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Adjust program break; routes through SYS_BRK (17, BSD break) on freebsd_arm64
    addr=0 queries current break; non-zero requests new break address
    :End Note
    Let syscall_num be freebsd_arm64_SYS_BRK()
    Return freebsd_arm64_syscall_1(syscall_num, addr)
End Process

Process called "freebsd_arm64_syscall_mmap" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer, prot as Integer, flags as Integer, fd as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Map memory; routes through SYS_MMAP (477, 64-bit offset-clean entry) on freebsd_arm64
    The 477 entry is the modern FreeBSD mmap with full 64-bit byte offset;
    legacy 71 is also present in this file but not used here
    :End Note
    Let syscall_num be freebsd_arm64_SYS_MMAP()
    Return freebsd_arm64_syscall_6(syscall_num, addr, length, prot, flags, fd, offset)
End Process

Process called "freebsd_arm64_syscall_munmap" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Unmap memory; routes through SYS_MUNMAP (73) on freebsd_arm64
    Let syscall_num be freebsd_arm64_SYS_MUNMAP()
    Return freebsd_arm64_syscall_2(syscall_num, addr, length)
End Process

Process called "freebsd_arm64_syscall_fstat" takes fd as Integer, statbuf as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Get file status by fd; routes through SYS_FSTAT (189) on freebsd_arm64
    statbuf points to a FreeBSD `struct stat` (size differs from Linux stat)
    :End Note
    Let syscall_num be freebsd_arm64_SYS_FSTAT()
    Return freebsd_arm64_syscall_2(syscall_num, fd, statbuf)
End Process

Process called "freebsd_arm64_syscall_lseek" takes fd as Integer, offset as Integer, whence as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Reposition file offset; routes through SYS_LSEEK (478, 64-bit-clean) on freebsd_arm64
    The 478 entry handles full 64-bit offsets natively (no _llseek needed)
    :End Note
    Let syscall_num be freebsd_arm64_SYS_LSEEK()
    Return freebsd_arm64_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, offset, whence)
End Process

Process called "freebsd_arm64_syscall_ioctl" takes fd as Integer, cmd as Integer, arg as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    @Reasoning
    Dispatcher-API entry-point for POSIX ioctl(2) on FreeBSD aarch64.
    SYS_ioctl is 54 (FreeBSD sys/sys/syscall.h, same number as amd64
    because FreeBSD shares a single syscall table across its supported
    architectures — only the calling convention differs). Three-arg
    shape (fd, request, argp). The aarch64 calling convention uses
    x0-x2 for arguments and x8 for the syscall number, with svc #0 as
    the syscall instruction.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Composes the syscall by calling freebsd_arm64_SYS_IOCTL() (returns
    54) and freebsd_arm64_syscall_3(54, fd, cmd, arg). The aarch64
    convention loads 54 into x8, fd into x0, cmd into x1, arg into
    x2, then svc #0; x0 holds the result on return (with the C flag
    set on error per FreeBSD's aarch64 convention — that conversion
    is handled inside syscall_3).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) dispatch in the FreeBSD kernel — one fd-table lookup and a
    driver vtable jump. The aarch64 svc #0 transition is the cheapest
    kernel-entry on the platform; ioctl overhead is dominated by the
    driver-side processing, not by this wrapper.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The FreeBSD kernel validates fd against the per-process file
    descriptor table and dispatches cmd through fileops.fo_ioctl.
    arg, if a pointer, is dereferenced by the kernel with the
    structure size implied by cmd; callers must size the buffer to
    match. MAC framework hooks may interpose on jailed or
    MAC-restricted processes; callers should expect EPERM in those
    contexts.
    @End Security_Scope
    :End Note

    Let syscall_num be freebsd_arm64_SYS_IOCTL()
    Return freebsd_arm64_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, cmd, arg)
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
FILE PERMISSION MODE CONSTANTS
============================================================================
:End Note

@Reasoning
File mode constants exposed by the cross-platform dispatcher's bare-name
API. FreeBSD uses the BSD-historical `mode_t` encoding, identical at the
permission-bit level to every other POSIX system: the low 9 bits are the
rwxrwxrwx permission triplet, encoded octally as 0644 (rw-r--r--) and
0755 (rwxr-xr-x). The values below are the decimal equivalents of those
octal constants, as required by the syscall ABI which treats the mode
argument as a plain integer.
Source: FreeBSD `sys/sys/stat.h` S_IRUSR=0400, S_IWUSR=0200, S_IRGRP=0040,
S_IWGRP=0020, S_IROTH=0004, S_IWOTH=0002, S_IXUSR=0100, S_IXGRP=0010,
S_IXOTH=0001. 0644 = 0400|0200|0040|0004 = 420 decimal. 0755 =
0400|0200|0100|0040|0010|0004|0001 = 493 decimal.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Nullary Process accessors returning the constant integer values. The
dispatcher's `MODE_0644 from Syscall` lookup resolves to this proc on
freebsd_arm64 targets via the bare-name route established in Wave 1.
Wave 2 will rename to `freebsd_arm64_MODE_0644`; Wave 1 keeps the bare
form to match the still-bare dispatcher.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
These accessors are constant returns; the compiler is expected to inline
them at every call site, leaving zero call overhead. Do not introduce any
runtime computation here.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a file permission constant carries no security state. Callers
who use the returned value as a `mode` argument to `creat`/`open(O_CREAT)`/
`mkdir`/`chmod` are responsible for ensuring the requested permission
matches the intended access policy. World-readable (0644) is appropriate
for non-sensitive files; group-and-world-executable (0755) is appropriate
for binaries and directories. On FreeBSD the effective umask further
masks the requested mode at creation time; callers needing exact mode
bits must `umask(0)` before file creation or `fchmod` afterwards.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "freebsd_arm64_MODE_0644" returns Integer:
    Return 420  Note: 0644 octal = rw-r--r--
End Process

Process called "freebsd_arm64_MODE_0755" returns Integer:
    Return 493  Note: 0755 octal = rwxr-xr-x
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
FILE SEEK WHENCE CONSTANTS
============================================================================
:End Note

@Reasoning
The `whence` argument to `lseek(2)` selects how the supplied offset is
interpreted: SEEK_SET (0) measures from the start of the file, SEEK_CUR
(1) measures relative to the current file position, SEEK_END (2)
measures relative to end-of-file. FreeBSD inherits these values from
the BSD heritage and they match the POSIX specification and every other
POSIX-conformant kernel. These match the bare-name dispatcher's
expectations and the `syscall_lseek` wrapper's `whence` parameter.
FreeBSD additionally defines SEEK_DATA (3) and SEEK_HOLE (4) for sparse
file traversal; those are outside the 66-proc dispatcher surface and
not exposed here.
Source: FreeBSD `sys/sys/unistd.h` SEEK_SET=0, SEEK_CUR=1, SEEK_END=2;
POSIX.1-2017 §lseek.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Nullary Process accessors returning the constant integer values. The
dispatcher routes `SEEK_SET from Syscall` to this proc on freebsd_arm64
targets via the bare-name pattern still in force during Wave 1. Bodies
are non-side-effecting and trivially inlinable.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; compiler-inlined at the call site. No runtime cost.
Avoid wrapping these in additional indirection; the dispatcher already
selects the platform-correct value at the dispatch boundary.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a seek-whence constant has no security implications on its
own. Callers that pass user-influenced `offset` values into `lseek`
with these whence flags MUST validate the resulting absolute file
position against the file's permitted range; an attacker-controlled
negative offset combined with SEEK_END can yield an unexpected
position prior to file start, which FreeBSD's `lseek(2)` will reject
with EINVAL. Sparse-file callers that need SEEK_DATA/SEEK_HOLE must
use the SYS_LSEEK syscall directly with the platform-specific whence
values 3 and 4, which are outside this dispatcher's portable surface.
@End Security_Scope

